Compile/run:
     - Compile using
            make MetroSim
     - run executable with
            ./MetroSim stationsFile passFile [commands]


Program Purpose:
To run a simulation of Metro Simulator.

Acknowledgements: 
I used the posts on https://cplusplus.com/ to understand the vector and list 
classes.

Files: 

main.cpp:
     Reads in files and creates a query in which the Metro Simulation can run.

MetroSim.cpp:
     Implements the MetroSim class and provides functions for it. Includes a
     function in the case that a command file is provided for the Simulation.

MetroSim.h:
     Interface of MetroSim class.

stations.txt:
     an example file containing a list of stations.

test_commands.txt:
     sample list of commands that you could give to the simulator

the_metroSim:
     reference implementation for students to see how 

PassengerQueue.cpp:
     Implements a queue of Passengers that models the stations and specific
     cars on the train.

PassengerQueue.h:
     Interface of PassengerQueue class.

Passenger.cpp:
     Implements the Passenger class. Assumes that when a Passenger is 
     constructed, it will have an id, starting station, and ending station.
     Allows clients to print out the passenger's information.

Passenger.h:
     Interface of the Passenger class.

Makefile:
     Contains neccessary information to compile the program using the 
     "make MetroSim" command.

unit_tests.h:
     Contains tests for the PassengerQueue class. 

README:
     Contains answers to questions provided at the end of the spec

Architectural Overview:
     The whole simulation is contained in the MetroSim class. In MetroSim, the
     train is represented by a vector of PassengerQueues and its current 
     location as a pointer to a PassengerQueue inside of that vector. Each
     PassengerQueue represents a station, where every passenger in the Queue
     aims to depart the train at the same station. Additionally, the stations 
     themselves are represented by a vector of PassengerQueues. Each station
     is represented by a struct that has the number that the station was read
     in from the station file, a string denoting the name of the station, and
     the PassengerQueue that represents the queue of Passengers. 


Data Structures:
Vectors and Lists
     I used vectors for the list of stations because I typically needed to
     identify which station a passenger should be added to. In these cases, 
     it was more effective to use a vector because of its easy access to all
     of the elements in the vector. On the other hand, for Passenger Queues, 
     I used queues because it was more efficient at storing passengers and 
     dispensing them at their desired locations. 


Testing:

I tested my final submission of the project by comparing its output to the 
provided diff file. For the first part, I used an unit test to ensure the
correct output was given. Additionally, I manually created new input files to
test against my program and the demo program. 


Part that you found most difficult:

I found the most challenging part of the assignment to be moving the train.

Time Spent: 10 hours
